1. Singleton Pattern
Singleton Pattern ensures that only one object of a class is created throughout the application.
It provides a global access point to that object.
It is useful when multiple objects can cause inconsistency.
This pattern saves memory and controls resource usage.
Commonly used for configuration, logging, and cache management.

2. Factory Method Pattern
Factory Method Pattern provides a way to create objects without exposing the creation logic to the client.
Instead of using the new keyword directly, the client requests an object from a factory.
The factory decides which object to create based on the input provided.
This reduces dependency between the client and implementation classes.
It makes the application easy to extend and maintain.
Example: Creating UPI, Credit Card, or Net Banking payment objects.

3. Abstract Factory Pattern
Abstract Factory Pattern is used to create families of related objects.
Instead of creating one object, it creates a group of related objects that work together.
The client interacts with interfaces and does not know the actual implementation classes.
This pattern ensures consistency among related objects.
It improves flexibility and makes switching between object families easy.
Example: Light Theme Factory and Dark Theme Factory creating buttons and text boxes.

4.Builder Pattern

  Builder Pattern is used to create complex objects step-by-step.
  It separates the object construction process from the final object representation.
  This pattern is useful when an object has many optional fields.
  It improves code readability and avoids constructors with too many parameters.
  The same building process can create different versions of an object.
  Example: Creating a User object with name, age, email, phone, and address.

5.Prototype Pattern

  Prototype Pattern creates new objects by cloning an existing object.
  Instead of creating an object from scratch, a copy of an existing object is used.
  This improves performance when object creation is expensive or time-consuming.
  The cloned object can be modified independently without affecting the original object.
  It reduces the cost of repeatedly creating similar objects.
  Example: Cloning an Employee template or Document template.
  